## What happened

**Apple removed DSA support from its Security framework**, and .NET on macOS delegates to the OS crypto libraries. In .NET 11, Microsoft dropped the macOS DSA back-end entirely, so `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. (Linux/Windows still work because they use OpenSSL and CNG respectively, both of which still support DSA.)

## How to fix it

You have two practical options:

### Option 1 – Use a managed crypto library (recommended)

Replace the built-in `DSA` calls with **BouncyCastle**, which is pure managed code and works on every platform:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

// Import the public key (from SubjectPublicKeyInfo / DER bytes)
var pubKey = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(spkiBytes);

// Verify
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA"); // match your legacy hash
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

### Option 2 – Use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS

Install OpenSSL (`brew install openssl`) and use `DSAOpenSsl`:

```csharp
using System.Security.Cryptography;

DSA dsa = OperatingSystem.IsMacOS()
    ? new DSAOpenSsl()          // requires OpenSSL dylib on PATH
    : DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(spkiBytes, out _);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(message, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

This is fragile (requires Homebrew OpenSSL at runtime), so **Option 1 is strongly preferred** for cross-platform reliability.

### Long-term

If you control the signing side, migrate to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — DSA is a legacy algorithm and support will continue to shrink across platforms.
